title: For Sale:  NEF New England Firearms Pardner Pump 12ga Home Defense Shotgun (870 clone)
postcontent:
NEF New England Firearms Pardner Pump 12ga Home Defense Shotgun. 12 gauge, 3" chamber (will shoot 2 3/4" and 3" shells). 6 round capacity (5 in the magazine plus 1 in the chamber, one round higher than the 870). Model number is NP1-P18

This is a Remington 870 clone, manufactured for NEF (who is now owned by Remington coincidentally). In my opinion, the quality of this gun is superior to that of the current generation Remington 870 Express guns, of which it is a copy.

Gun does show some minor wear from racking and storage, but it is the kind of thing that you'd expect to see after a week or two of use. I was told the gun is unfired when I bought it, and believe that to be the case (I have not fired it since I purchased it). My best guess is that it was purchased, unboxed, and loaded and stuck in a corner until I bought it.

This is an ideal home defense gun, esp for someone on a budget. It's even factory drilled and tapped to accept a scope or red-dot sight, so you could even use it for hunting if you were so inclined.

Price is firm.

Under the left grip is "83"
Under the trigger guard is "83"
On the loading level is "83"
On the front of the cylinder is PN
The serial number on the bottom of the butt is 2919

title: For Sale:  Antique Turkish Mauser M1887
postcontent:
The Model 1887's was the first contract rifle the Ottomans bought from Mauser. The Ottomans placed their first order with Waffenfabrik Mauser for 500,000 rifles and 50,000 carbines patterned after the Gewehr 71/84 bolt action rifle. This black powder rifle was chambered for the 9.5x60R military round. The rifle held 8 rounds in the tubular magazine. The Ottomans eventually made the switch to smokeless powder after accepting 270,000 of these rifles and the remainder of the contract was filled with the Model of 1890.

This is a rare rifle and in good condition.  Made for the Turkish army in the late 1800's.  It is the last black powder rifle made by Mauser before turning to the smokeless 8mm rounds.  It is missing the nose cap and the cleaning rod.  The barrel is in good shape as well as the bolt.  The bolt is miss matched.  It fires the 9.5x60mm round.  It would be a great piece to any collection.

The same rifle on the link below sold for $995 in December

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1873 First Model - Collectors Item
postcontent:
Gun: Winchester 1873 Carbine in .44-40

Appraised Value:  $6,500 to $7,000 and possibly up to $8,500

History:  The Winchester 1873 was the most popular lever action repeating rifle made in America.  Introduced in 1873 and produced through 1919, there were over 720,000 guns made.  There were three Models of the 1873, with only minor differences except for the dust cover.  This particular gun has serial # 22741, placing production in late 1876 and making it a First Model.  This 1873 carbine has a 20” round barrel, barrel bands and is a 44 WCF (.44-40) caliber.  The gun is rated between fair and good condition.  The barrel metal retains about 50% original bluing, the surface is pitted in 2 places and the worn but lettering is readable.  The receiver is also worn with less than 10% bluing as patina with most on the rear receiver and finger lever.   The wood is in good condition, without cracks but with a number of handling marks down both sides of forearm and stock.  The stock has the correct carbine metal butt plate with trap door.  Dust cover and cleaning rod are missing.  The correct original front and rear non-adjustable leaf sights are still on the gun with the latter having graduations from 100-300 yards. Bore is in good shape with 75% rifling.  Overall, this gun looks all original and would fall somewhere near good condition (by NRA Standards).  In 2013, the retail value of this carbine would lie somewhere between $6500 and $7,000.  The value of the rifle could go to $8,500 for the age and caliber, depending on the buyer.

If you have any questions shoot us an email.

The subject of this review is my own Bushmaster XM-15-E2S that was made in Windham, (I got mine!). It is an A3 model with an A2 style fixed buttstock, handle sight, 20 inch heavy barrel with 1 turn in 9 inch twist rifling, bayonet lug, birdcage flash suppressor and it came with a 30 round magazine.
This Bushmaster rifle is chambered for .223 Remington and 5.56mm NATO rounds and is marked as such, so both may be safely used. I don't recommend that these rounds be used interchangeably in any firearm that is not specifically marked for both. There are many that believe that the .223 Remington and the 5.56mm NATO round are the same but in fact they are not. According to Small Arms Manufacturers Institute, Inc, (SAAMI), it is unsafe to fire 5.56mm NATO rounds in firearms chambered for .223 Remington. If you do a little Google searching around the Internet you can find the technical information related to that subject if it interests you. Be careful and only use the ammunition your firearm is designed to fire safely.

title: For Sale:  223 Brass
postcontent:
Before you peruse this listing, you have to ask yourself

Am I a bad enough dude to buy some brass?

Do I really think I can handle the sheer awesomeness that is a cardboard box full of raw heart-throbbing (admittedly, fired) 223? Can these little guys pack a punch? You betcha. Can they blow a hole the size of my massive ego into whatever's downrange? Oh yes.

Do I wish I had some brass? Absolutely.

You know you want it. I know you want it. Go ahead, I'll make you an offer you can't refuse.

Did I count up these suckers? Hell yeah I can count -- but only up to 722. Fortunately, that's the exact number of empty shells I have. I tried to count up the other miscellaneous empties I have lying around, but 722 is my limit. Pick up these, the rest are yours if you want 'em -- and you can take that to the bank.

Though, in retrospect, taking firearm components, even empty brass, to the bank may not be the wisest plan. Don't do that. Laugh all the way home on the great deal you got on some honest-to-god once-fired reloading supplies!

$40. Or the best offer. Or the first offer. Or a trade -- come and get 'em gents!
